---

<Base title="The tariff" description="Why this UK solar + battery + Predbat home runs Octopus Agile import with fixed 12p export — and what happened when Octopus Flux closed a month before our install.">
  <section class="reveal">
    <p class="kicker">Octopus Agile import · Outgoing fixed 12p export</p>
    <h1>The tariff</h1>
    <p style="max-width:46rem">
      The tariff choice matters as much as the hardware: it decides what every stored kWh is
      worth. Ours changed <em>one month before install day</em>, and the story is instructive if
      you're planning a battery system around any time-of-use tariff.
    </p>
  </section>

  <h2>The Flux plot twist</h2>
  <p style="max-width:46rem">
    The original business case was built on <strong>Octopus Flux</strong> — the classic battery
    tariff with a cheap overnight window and a 30p evening export peak. The plan: charge cheap,
    force-export the battery into the 16:00–19:00 peak, profit. Then, in <strong>March 2026</strong>,
    Flux (and Intelligent Octopus Flux) closed to new customers. Install: April 2026. Plan: dead.
  </p>
  <div class="note red">
    <p><strong>Lesson one:</strong> never build a multi-year payback case on a single tariff
    surviving. Tariffs are products; products get withdrawn. Model your second-best option too —
    we hadn't, and re-planning under time pressure wasn't fun.</p>
  </div>

  <h2>What we run now</h2>
  <table>
    <thead><tr><th>Side</th><th>Tariff</th><th>Shape</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Import</td><td>Octopus Agile</td><td>Half-hourly dynamic pricing, published ~16:00 for the next day, capped at £1/kWh. Cheapest slots ~13–15p, evening peak ~32–37p.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Export</td><td>Outgoing Octopus (fixed)</td><td>Flat 12p/kWh, any time. Boring on purpose — a guaranteed floor.</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p style="max-width:46rem">
    Surprisingly, losing the 30p export peak cost only ~10% of the projected year-1 return.
    The reason: under Agile the battery's job flips from <em>exporting at peak</em> to
    <em>not importing at peak</em>. Avoiding a 35p import is worth more than a 30p export ever
    was, and Predbat reorganised the whole strategy around that by itself the day we changed the
    rate sensors. Only true surplus export (battery full, house satisfied) took the haircut from
    30p to 12p.
  </p>
  <div class="note">
    <p><strong>The upgrade path:</strong> Agile Outgoing (half-hourly export pricing, uncapped, no
    exit fees) can beat a flat 12p for battery owners who export selectively into evening spikes —
    winter wholesale prices sometimes clear 50p–£1/kWh. The plan is to switch once
    <a href="/stats/">the data</a> shows our would-be Agile export revenue reliably beating 12p.
    That comparison is exactly the kind of question this site's dataset exists to answer.</p>
  </div>

  <h2>Why Octopus at all?</h2>
  <p style="max-width:46rem">
    Higher flat export rates exist elsewhere (E.ON ~16.5p, British Gas ~15p) — but they require
    importing with the same supplier on a flat or simple ToU tariff, and for a Predbat home the
    cheap-import arbitrage on Agile is the bigger prize. Octopus also has the best API in the
    business, which is what the <a href="/stack/">whole automation stack</a> hangs off.
  </p>

